Explore and Summarize Data by Ashish

Dataset Overview:

This tidy data set contains 1,599 red wines with 13 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

My Point Of View of Analysis:

Which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines?

Univariate Analysis:

What is the structure of your dataset?

There were 1599 obs. of 13 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main interest was ‘quality’ as it is the key factor of wine’s taste.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

‘alcohol’ & ‘pH’ will also play a important ingredient for wines taste.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

‘quality.rating’ was created to show the ratings of the quality.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the

form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I removed variable ‘X’ from dataset as it was of no use.

There were many outliers(can be seen above in Box Plots & Histograms). To know the actual distribution many variables were log transformed.

Bivariate Plots Section:

Through ‘GGally’ package we can see the correlation between the variables:

Variable’s with strong Positive Correlation:

  • alcohol & quality
  • free sulfur dioxide & total sulfur dioxide
  • density & fixed acidity
  • citric acid & fixed acidity

Variable’s with strong Negative Correlation:

  • density & alcohol
  • pH & citric acid
  • volatile acidity & fixed acidity
  • pH & fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity & citric acid

Same thing can be visualised from the above graphs.

Now, we will compare our main intrest i.e ‘quality.rating’ with alcohol,

As we have seen in above chart quality and alcohol are having a positive correlation, which can also be seen from above box plots.

As we can see that ‘quality.rating’ as Excellent are having alcohol quantity more than ‘Bad’ and ‘Average’.

Sample size for ‘Average’ looks more than other two i.e. ‘Excellent’ & ‘Bad’.

Bivariate Analysis:

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Our main intrest was with ‘quality’, which was having a positive correlation with ‘alcohol’. The alcohol which was having grade ‘7’ and ‘8’ were having good amount of alcohol.

Red Wine having less volatile acidity were having good quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Density is strongly correlated with alcohol (negatively).

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Positive:

  • fixed.acidity:citirc.acid = 0.7
  • fixed.acidity:density = 0.7

Negative:

  • fixed.acidity:pH = 0.7

Multivariate Plots Section:

I will be plotting alcohol, density, sulaphates, quality and volatile acidity as they were strongly related with ‘quality’ of red wine.

As we can see from the plot that red wine with quality ‘8’ is around left most part of the graph. Through this we can incur that red wine with less volatile acidity are good in quality.

Same goes with ‘density’ also. Wines having less density are having good quality.

Multivariate Analysis:

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Since ‘quality’ was highly correlated with density, sulaphates, alcohol and volatile acidity.So I plotted sulaphates, alcohol, volatile acidity and quality (In Multivariate Plot 1). So we can see that with increase in volatile acid quality is decreasing.

In Multivariate Plot 2, I plotted sulaphates, alcohol, density and quality. So here we can see that with increase in density quality is decreasing.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Here I did not find any thing unusual or interesting may be I dont have domain knowledge to check those variables which may impact analysis. It was purely based on the correlations.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

Yes, I created three models. R-squared values were very less for all the three models(Higher is better with 1 being the best),which were not as much convincing to declare as a linear model for this dataset.

Here p-value indicates there is a significant relationship described by the model because the values are less than 0.05.So we reject the null hypothesis.

Plot Three

Description Three

‘quality’ is highly correlated with density, sulaphates, alcohol and volatile acidity. With the increase in density and volatile acidity, the quality of Red Wine increases.

Reflection

Red Wine data set contains information on 1599 wines across 13 variables. Then exploratory data analysis was done in which at first a univariate, then bivariate and finally multivariate examinations were performed to know relations between its features.

And I have the feeling that some interesting relations(Multivariate) may have been left aside among the many permutations of variables in the dataset. I think good domain knowledge about red wine would have helped a lot while doing analysis of this dataset. As I could have known relation between variables which impacts the quality. This would have certainly improve the accuracy of the prediction models.

Another challenge was factoring the quality variable, which was rectified by reviewer how to efficiently with ordinal variables.
